---
import Doc from '../layouts/Doc.astro';
import FeatureRow from '../components/FeatureRow.astro';
import Callout from '../components/Callout.astro';
import Button from '../components/Button.astro';
import MonoLabel from '../components/MonoLabel.astro';
import StatusPill from '../components/StatusPill.astro';
---

<Doc
  title="Chips for platforms — BYO runtime, plug into bridge + network intelligence"
  description="For enterprises with internal agent capability already running on Bedrock, Azure Foundry, or in-house — plug into the bridge and Level B priors via packages/sdk-a2a-server."
  pageLabel="FOR PLATFORMS"
  eyebrow="CATEGORY B · ENTERPRISES WITH INTERNAL AGENT CAPABILITY"
  heading={`<em>Don't</em> rebuild your runtime.<br/>Plug into the <em>network<span class="dot">.</span></em>`}
  lede="You have an agent on Bedrock, Foundry, or in-house. You don't need a new runtime — you need the consumer-consented context network and the cross-enterprise behavior priors that no single cloud can give you."
>
  <FeatureRow number="01" label="THE PROBLEM" heading="Hyperscalers cannot give you Level B.">
    <p>
      Bedrock and Foundry could in principle aggregate cross-enterprise signal — they host enterprise agents.
      <em>They can't credibly do it</em> because their commercial relationships compete with the enterprises
      they'd aggregate from. You won't trust AWS with your conversion patterns when AWS is simultaneously
      selling cloud services to the rest of your market and operating Amazon's own retail business.
    </p>
    <p>
      Solo agents — even excellent ones — are <em>structurally cold</em>. Every consumer interaction starts
      from your data alone. Every objection pattern, every conversion-by-context insight, every clarifying
      question that works in your category has to be discovered by you.
    </p>
  </FeatureRow>

  <FeatureRow number="02" label="THE INTEGRATION" heading="One SDK. Bridge + Network Intelligence.">
    <p>
      Install <code>@chips/sdk-a2a-server</code> in your existing A2A runtime — Bedrock AgentCore, Azure AI
      Foundry, Salesforce, or in-house. The SDK wires:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li><em>Bridge response handlers</em> — your agent can call <code>bridge.query</code> against the Chips network with consumer-consented scopes.</li>
      <li><em>Outcome event emitters</em> — Level A flows to your CDP, Level B flows to the Chips aggregation pipeline.</li>
      <li><em>Level B prior consumption</em> — system-prompt augmentation, reranking signal, conversation-state heuristics.</li>
      <li><em>Policy hooks</em> — the bridge utility model (Loop 5) suggests queries your agent might not have considered.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      <em>You keep your runtime. You keep your LLM choice. You keep your operational footprint.</em> You add
      the network as a thin API layer that compounds.
    </p>
  </FeatureRow>

  <FeatureRow number="03" label="THE PRICING" heading="Unbundled Network Intelligence. Pay for the layer that compounds.">
    <p>
      For Category B enterprises who don't take the Chips runtime, <em>Network Intelligence is sold
      unbundled</em>: <strong>$499/mo</strong> for category-refined priors, <strong>$2,499/mo</strong> for
      bespoke. Plus standard handshake + bridge call meters.
    </p>
    <p>
      Worked example for a Category B enterprise on Bedrock who only buys NI + Bridge: bridge ~$7,500/mo +
      NI subscription $499/mo = <em>~$8,000/mo</em>. See <a href="/pricing">/pricing</a> for the full table.
    </p>
  </FeatureRow>

  <Callout variant="quote">
    <p>
      <strong>The unbundled NI subscription is the meter hyperscalers structurally cannot replicate.</strong>
      As Chips's network grows, Meter 5 value grows. As Bedrock and Foundry scale, their per-API price drops —
      but their Network Intelligence stays at zero.
    </p>
  </Callout>

  <FeatureRow number="04" label="WHO THIS IS FOR" heading="Enterprises shipping agents that recognize the structural gap.">
    <p>
      You're a good fit if you've already shipped an A2A agent on Bedrock / Azure / in-house, you know what
      your agent doesn't know, and you can name the conversion patterns you'd love to inherit from the rest of
      your category. <em>~200–500 mid-market enterprises globally fit this profile.</em>
    </p>
    <p>
      Common entry points: <StatusPill kind="emerald">AWS Bedrock AgentCore</StatusPill>
      <StatusPill kind="emerald">Azure AI Foundry</StatusPill>
      <StatusPill kind="emerald">Salesforce Agentforce</StatusPill>
      <StatusPill kind="emerald">In-house LangGraph / LlamaIndex</StatusPill>
    </p>
  </FeatureRow>

  <section class="cta-row">
    <div class="cta-row-inner">
      <div>
        <MonoLabel tone="emerald">PARTNERSHIPS · CATEGORY B</MonoLabel>
        <h3 class="cta-h">
          Plug in the network.<br />
          <em>Keep</em> the runtime.
        </h3>
      </div>
      <div class="cta-buttons">
        <Button href="mailto:hello@chips.dev?subject=Chips%20-%20platforms%20partnership" variant="primary">
          Talk to us
        </Button>
        <Button href="/how-it-works" variant="outline">How it works</Button>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</Doc>

<style>
  .cta-row {
    margin-top: 72px;
    padding: 48px 0 0;
    border-top: 1px solid var(--hair);
  }
  .cta-row-inner {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 1.4fr 1fr;
    gap: 32px;
    align-items: center;
  }
  .cta-h {
    font-family: var(--serif);
    font-size: clamp(1.6rem, 2vw + 0.5rem, 2.1rem);
    line-height: 1.15;
    letter-spacing: -0.018em;
    font-weight: 400;
    color: var(--ink);
    margin: 12px 0 0;
    max-width: 24ch;
  }
  .cta-h em {
    font-style: italic;
    color: var(--emerald);
  }
  .cta-buttons {
    display: flex;
    gap: 12px;
    flex-wrap: wrap;
    justify-content: flex-end;
  }
  @media (max-width: 900px) {
    .cta-row-inner { grid-template-columns: 1fr; }
    .cta-buttons { justify-content: flex-start; }
  }
</style>
